INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('thermal-comfort-older-adults-care-settings','FI','SEARCHED',0,'PROTOCOL: FULL (adversarial-searched 2026-05-10 session_2026-05-10f using native aliases)

STANDARD: STM asumisterveysohje (Ministry of Social Affairs and Health housing health guide): Health hazards below 18°C or above 26°C, never above 32°C. Heating season target 23-24°C, other seasons 21°C. Motiva and Sisäilmayhdistys (Indoor Air Association) recommend 20-22°C. No specific care-home standard found — guidance is residential.

Valvira (National Supervisory Authority for Welfare and Health) oversees care homes but no published temperature standard specific to elderly thermoregulation was found in FI-language search.

ADVERSARIAL: Finnish sources confirm elderly and young children need warmer environments ("heidän lämmönsäätelykykynsä on heikompi" — their thermoregulation ability is weaker) but no FI-specific research on dementia/thermoregulation was found. Evidence gap.

FINDING: FI general temperature guidance (Motiva, STM) exists at residential level but care-home specific guidance relies on Valvira operational oversight, not building standards. No equivalent to SV Folkhälsomyndigheten population-stratified guidance.

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- PMV-PPD not validated for elderly populations.
- "Symptomless cooling" documented in EN literature.
- FI: guidance is residential not care-specific. Evidence gap for muistisairaus (memory illness) thermal needs.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10 22:24','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');
