INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('thermal-comfort-older-adults-care-settings','JA','SEARCHED',2,'PROTOCOL: FULL (adversarial-searched 2026-05-10 session_2026-05-10f using native aliases)

STANDARD: No formal temperature standard in Japanese law for care facilities — "法律などで正式に定めた基準はありません." Facilities typically use 20-22°C winter guideline. MHLW notices (厚生労働省通知) provide temperature/humidity targets: Winter 18-20°C / 55-70% RH, Summer 24-28°C / 45-55% RH. Not building code.

ADVERSARIAL FINDING — Lewy body dementia (レビー小体型認知症): Causes DISTINCT thermoregulation problems from Alzheimer''s per JA clinical sources. Symptoms reported: 不適切な温度環境 (ending up in inappropriate temperature environments due to impaired judgment), skin vasodilation, excessive sweating, night sweats, possible hypothermia. BPC does not differentiate dementia subtypes for thermal design.

ADVERSARIAL: Half of Japanese emergency heatstroke patients are 65+. Indoor heatstroke is the dominant pattern. "エアコンが苦手" (discomfort with air conditioning) is a documented behavioral barrier specific to Japanese elderly. Care facility design must account for AC resistance behavior.

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- PMC7557728 (2020): "Symptomless cooling" in dementia — residents in cooler environments rated themselves as comfortable while objectively cold.
- PMV-PPD model not validated for elderly populations (based on young adult metabolic rates).
- WHO 18°C minimum; JA practice 20-22°C; no jurisdiction has mandatory building code for elderly-specific thermal comfort.
- JA-specific: MHLW notification system, not building code. Different regulatory approach from EU/Anglophone standards-based model.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10 23:09','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');
