German economic studies on Barrierefreiheit ROI limited. Demographic argument strong (aging population).

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- Same evidence base as construction-cost-data but focused on ECONOMICS argument (ROI, market value, demographic shifts).
- UK Equality Act business case studies. Canadian RHFAC cost-effectiveness data.
- Demographic argument: aging population makes accessibility investment economically rational.
ADVERSARIAL:
- Economic arguments conflate correlation (accessible buildings in desirable areas) with causation (accessibility adds value).
- ROI calculations depend heavily on discount rate, time horizon, and population assumptions.
- "Universal design premium" estimates vary 5× across studies (0.1% to 5%).
- No controlled economic experiment (accessible vs not) — all observational or modeled.
- Business case may not apply to residential, rural, or low-income contexts.
