INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('construction-cost-data','DE','SEARCHED',2,'PROTOCOL: FULL (adversarial-searched 2026-05-11 session_2026-05-10f using native aliases barrierefreies Bauen/Mehrkosten)

STANDARD: Germany has DETAILED cost research the batch note completely missed.

KEY STUDY: TERRAGON / Deutscher Städte- und Gemeindebund (DStGB), "Barrierefreies Bauen im Kostenvergleich" (April 2017) — analyzed 140-148 criteria from DIN 18040-2 in a Berlin 20-unit, 1,500 m² model project. Findings:
- 138 of 148 criteria achievable with NO cost premium (intelligent planning only)
- Only 10 criteria actually generate cost increase
- Full DIN 18040-2 compliance: +€21.50/m² wohnfläche = 1.26% of pure construction costs (KG 300+400)
- Cost-optimized barrier-free variant: +€9.20/m² = 0.54% of pure construction costs
- Of total investment costs (KG 100-700): 0.83% / 0.35% respectively
- 75 m² apartment: ~€1,600 additional cost for full barrier-free

CORROBORATION: Bundesfachstelle Barrierefreiheit (2024) gives a range of 0.86% to 1.7% Mehrkosten for fully barrier-free apartments to DIN standard, consistent with TERRAGON. Niedersachsen ministry cites this range.

GERMAN FUNDING: KfW "Altersgerecht Umbauen" program (€2,500-€5,000 per unit grant proposed by TERRAGON to extend to new construction).

CORRECTION: Prior batch note said "German DIN standards integrate accessibility into base construction cost. No separate DE cost study found." This was WRONG — the TERRAGON/DStGB 2017 study is exactly the kind of "separate DE cost study" the BPC was looking for. It provides the most rigorous quantitative cost decomposition in any jurisdiction.

ADVERSARIAL: The 0.35-1.26% range is significantly LOWER than the "1-5%" range some US sources cite. German methodology (KG cost group decomposition per DIN 276) is more granular than US ADA Network''s "less than 1%" claim. The German study uses a single Berlin project — generalizability across building types and German regions not established. Retrofit costs (Bestandsumbau) are 20-30% higher than new construction per current GREENOX practice data.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11 01:27','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('construction-cost-data','FR','SEARCHED',0,'PROTOCOL: FULL (cross-jurisdictional synthesis 2026-05-10 session_2026-05-10e)

French loi handicap 2005 mandated accessibility; cost premium studies limited.

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- US: ADA National Network claims "<1%" for new construction. Schroeder & Steinfeld 1979 (REF-00195): 0.12–0.5%. BUT 45+ years old.
- CA: RHFAC 2024 (REF-00300): 0.5% office / 1.5% K-12 school for retrofit. Industry-funded (RHF+HCMA), not independently peer-reviewed.
- ADA 20% rule: Alterations capped at 20% of project cost for path-of-travel.
ADVERSARIAL:
- "<1%" applies ONLY to new construction. Retrofit costs dramatically higher ($1.50-$9.00/sqft per RHFAC).
- Schroeder & Steinfeld 1979 is 45+ years old — construction costs/methods radically changed.
- No peer-reviewed meta-analysis of accessibility construction cost premiums exists.
- "New build vs retrofit" is fundamental confound in all cost claims.
- Cost estimates methodology-dependent: what counts as "accessibility cost" vs "good design" is subjective.
PROTOCOL COMPLIANCE: FULL — cross-jurisdictional synthesis, protocol fields populated.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T21:34:02Z','session_2026-05-10e-slug3-adversarial');
