INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','DE','SEARCHED',9,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: Wegweiser Demenz (BMFSFJ — Bundesministerium für Familie, Senioren, Frauen und Jugend, German federal dementia portal). DIN 18040-1/2 (accessibility, applies but does not specifically cover dementia cognition). Deutsche Alzheimer Gesellschaft guidance. DBSV (Deutscher Blinden- und Sehbehindertenverband) cross-referenced for visual aspects. Curaviva (Swiss) widely referenced. Healing Architecture concept. Key academic source: Monika Holfeld (architect, color designer, barrier-free planning specialist). REGULATORY STATUS: No mandatory federal standard specifically for dementia spatial design. DIN 18040 covers physical accessibility but not dementia-specific cognitive accessibility. Wegweiser Demenz is information portal not law. Federal funding programs (e.g., for dementia-friendly remodeling) reference principles but do not mandate specific values. KEY PRINCIPLES: (1) Small groups (5-15 residents; >20 shows negative effects). (2) Avoid long straight corridors (cause restlessness, loss of vitality/identity); prefer L- or H-shaped layouts. (3) Color concepts on doors and handrails. (4) Dark floors perceived as barriers (can deter undesired exit). (5) Biographic pictures at room doors replace numbers (min 22mm font for names). (6) Different wall colors per room/zone for orientation. (7) Avoid floor patterns (perceived as holes). (8) Mirrors can cause confusion (elevator mirror perceived as corridor; bathroom mirror perceived as another person). (9) Noise dampening (lärm causes increased agitation/aggression). (10) Good lighting without glare; supplementary indirect lighting. Research finding (contradicting common practice): One study found color-based wayfinding helps less than landmark furniture and large floor numbers. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: DE has no formal regulatory framework for dementia spatial design comparable to DK Mærkningsordning or SE Socialstyrelsen guidelines — primarily guidance-level. Sources: wegweiser-demenz.de (BMFSFJ), nullbarriere.de/farbkonzepte-im-alter, b-k-p.net/demenzsensible-architektur, agesuit.com, raumunddemenz.de/FLURWELTEN, dbz.de/Holfeld-Farbgestaltung. CONFIDENCE: high for principles; medium for absence of mandatory standard (DIN does exist but doesn''t specifically address dementia).','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:13:03.293417+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','FR','SEARCHED',8,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: EHPAD (Établissement d''Hébergement pour Personnes Âgées Dépendantes) — French nursing home regulatory framework. UHR (Unités d''Hébergement Renforcées) — Reinforced Housing Units for severe Alzheimer''s, formally defined in the Code de l''Action Sociale et des Familles. PASA (Pôle d''Activités et de Soins Adaptés) — Adapted Activities and Care Pole, formally defined. Fondation Médéric Alzheimer (major research foundation, 20+ year history). Government portal: pour-les-personnes-agees.gouv.fr. REGULATORY STATUS: UHR and PASA are formally regulated units with mandatory architectural features (secure garden access, secure perimeter, max group size). Specific spatial design specifications (colors, signage, materials) are guidance-level, not mandatory thresholds. KEY PRINCIPLES: (1) Wide, clear corridors. (2) Calming, harmonious colors with avoidance of wall-door same-color (door "disappears"). (3) Warm/saturated/luminous colors more visible to aging eyes. (4) Warm colors in living spaces; cool/calming in care/rest spaces. (5) Multisensory signage: pictograms + contrasting colors + textures. (6) Chronobiological lighting (varies intensity/color temperature to reinforce temporal cues, reduces "sundowning" syndrome). (7) Secure therapeutic gardens. (8) Snoezelen rooms for controlled sensory stimulation. (9) Avoid sensory over-stimulation. (10) Biographic landmarks rather than written signage (since residents are oriented through familiar reference points, not abstract directional language). UHR principles per pour-les-personnes-agees.gouv.fr: convivial non-institutional environment; orientation and ambulation supported; balance of autonomy and intimacy; avoid sensory over-stimulation. Sources: ehpad-magazine.com/larchitecture-vecteur-de-bientraitance, flores-amo.fr/programmation-architecturale-unites-alzheimer, zenior.care/guides/unite-alzheimer, gerontim.com/EHPAD-6-points-cles, pour-les-personnes-agees.gouv.fr. CONFIDENCE: high for UHR/PASA regulatory framework; medium for specific design principles (multiple practitioner sources but not from a single mandatory standard).','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:15:02.510991+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','DA','SEARCHED',8,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: SBi-anvisning 259 (2014, "Plejeboliger for personer med demens — indledende spørgsmål") and SBi-anvisning 263 ("Plejeboliger for personer med demens — detaljer og eksempler"). Statens Byggeforskningsinstitut/Aalborg University. Socialstyrelsen 2004 publication "Indretning af plejecentre – for svage ældre og mennesker med demens" (Design of care centers for frail elderly and people with dementia). Trafik-, Bygge- og Boligstyrelsens Mærkningsordning for demensegnede plejeboliger (formal Ministerial labelling scheme for dementia-friendly care homes). Nationalt Videnscenter for Demens (National Knowledge Centre for Dementia). REGULATORY STATUS: Mærkningsordning is a formal ministerial labelling scheme; SBi guidance is technical guidance, widely cited but not legally binding in itself. KEY PRINCIPLES (from SBi 259 §3.3.2 Farveforståelse): (1) Strategic color contrast for orientation (door frames different from walls; doors different colors; toilet/sink/cistern contrast). (2) Color coding by function — all bathroom doors same color. (3) Avoid sharp/strong contrasting colors (overwhelming/confusing). (4) Avoid complex/busy patterns. (5) Avoid black (perceived as shadows or holes). (6) Avoid reflective surfaces (cause confusion, can be misperceived as another person). (7) Wayfinding through landmark pictures and reference points. Mærkningsordning 4 key areas: wayfinding/orientation; nature connection and sensory stimulation; homeliness/atmosphere; daylight + artificial light. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: DK has a formal MINISTERIAL LABELLING SCHEME (Mærkningsordning) — unusual; most other jurisdictions only have technical guidance. Sources: sst.dk/Indretning-af-plejecentre (Socialstyrelsen 2004), sbi.dk/anvisning259, sonovision.dk/maerkning-af-demensboliger, ft.dk/PDF-INDRETNING-AF-PLEJEBOLIGER. CONFIDENCE: high — primary regulatory framework (Mærkningsordning) and primary technical guidance (SBi 259, 263) confirmed.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:13:03.293417+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','FI','SEARCHED',9,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: **Ympäristöopas 2018 — Muisti- ja ikäystävällinen asuminen ja asuinympäristö** (Environmental Guide 2018 — Memory- and Age-Friendly Living and Environment), published by Valtioneuvoston kanslia (Finnish government), authored by Päivi Topo (Ikäinstituutti/Age Institute) and architect Helinä Kotilainen — comprehensive 6-chapter government guidance. Muistiliitto (Finnish Memory Association — muistiliitto.fi) authoritative public guidance. Suomen muistiasiantuntijat ry (SUMU — Finnish Memory Experts). Sujuva (accessibility guidance with specific lighting parameter values). Kotitapaturma.fi (Home Accident Prevention) — practical guidance for dementia-safe home. Key concept: ''Muistiystävällinen'' (memory-friendly) — distinct term used systematically in Finnish guidance vs. ''demens''/dementia. REGULATORY STATUS: Ympäristöopas 2018 is government guidance, not legally binding mandatory regulation. Building accessibility (RakMK F1/Decree 241/2017) covers general accessibility, not specifically dementia spatial cognition. Funding tied to municipal social services, not specifically dementia spatial design. KEY PRINCIPLES: (1) Bold use of colors for orientation and de-emphasizing back-of-house. (2) Tummuuskontrasti (luminance contrast) more important than hue (consistent with luminance-contrast slug research). (3) Practical test: black-and-white photograph to verify spatial contrast. (4) Darker floor than walls = stability sensation for walking. (5) Wall-corner color differences support spatial perception. (6) Furniture contrasts with floor and walls. (7) Reflectance recommendations: ceiling 0.7-0.9, floor 0.2-0.6 (from Sujuva). (8) Light needs increase with age. (9) Chronobiological lighting mimicking circadian cycle. (10) Direct outdoor garden access reduces aggression, improves cognition (per SUMU). (11) Multisensory wayfinding cues — nature-based cues are easily interpreted without complex cognitive processing. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: FI integrates ''muistiystävällinen'' concept formally with environmental design through government guidance, but lacks the formal certification (DK Mærkningsordning) or funding-linkage (NO Husbanken) of other Nordic countries. Sources: julkaisut.valtioneuvosto.fi/Ympäristöopas-2018-Muisti-ikäystävällinen, muistiliitto.fi/muistiystavallinen-ymparisto, vanheneminen.fi/muistiystavallinen-koti, sumut.fi/ymparisto (SUMU), sujuva.info/Valaistus (lighting params), kotitapaturma.fi/muistiturvallinen. CONFIDENCE: high for guidance content and principles.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:15:02.510991+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','EN','SEARCHED',11,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11 (UPGRADE from 110-char pre-remediation stub). KEY INSTRUMENTS: **DSDC (Dementia Services Development Centre, University of Stirling)** — globally most influential standard-setter; operates world''s most established product accreditation programme for dementia-friendly design (DSDC 1A accreditation). Active since 1990s. **EADDAT (Environments for Ageing and Dementia Design Assessment Tool)** — University of Stirling 2022, replaces Dementia Design Audit Tool 2008. Adopted by Kirklees Council (first local authority) and Transport for London (Sustainable Development Framework). Three-tier assessment system. **Kirklees Dementia Design Guidance** — Kirklees Council guidance based on DSDC standards. **NHS England Dementia-Friendly Environments Guidance for Assessors** — part of PLACE (Patient-Led Assessments of the Care Environment). **Health Building Notes (HBNs) and Health Technical Memoranda (HTMs)** — NHS technical specifications. **Equality Act 2010** — legal basis for "reasonable adjustments." Housing LIN (Learning and Improvement Network) — extensive resource library. **BS 8300-2:2018** dementia annex (overlap with luminance-contrast slug). REGULATORY STATUS: Per DSDC Director Prof. June Andrews: "There is as yet no regulatory standard for dementia design." DSDC has 25 years of experience but cannot check every claim. Equality Act 2010 imposes ''reasonable adjustments'' duty but no specific dementia building thresholds. NHS PLACE assessments are mandatory for healthcare environments. UK is acknowledged global leader in dementia design GUIDANCE but lacks mandatory regulatory thresholds. KEY RESEARCH FINDINGS (DSDC and partners): (1) Signs with realistic 3D imagery recognized 40% more accurately than abstract icons by people with moderate dementia. (2) DSDC/NHS Scotland: Improving corridor lighting from 150 to 300 lux reduces falls 25%, improves independent navigation 20%. (3) Color-coded environments reduce wayfinding errors 25-40% in care settings. (4) Multi-sensory wayfinding approaches reduce disorientation incidents 35% vs visual-only (Journal of Alzheimer''s Disease 2019). (5) Karolinska Institute + German DZNE: allocentric navigation (hippocampus-based mental map) declines early in Alzheimer''s; egocentric navigation (parietal cortex, landmark-based) persists longer → emphasizes visible landmarks. KEY PRINCIPLES: signage with realistic imagery + simple words; min 1.21m sign height; high contrast text; consistent design language; familiar domestic styling; circular garden paths leading back to building; raised planting beds; secure non-institutional boundaries; circadian-supporting lighting (cooler bright by day, warmer dim by evening) to reduce sundowning; memory boxes/personal items near bedroom doors; bathroom doors visibly different; clear sight lines. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: UK has the world''s most comprehensive evidence base and accreditation system (DSDC), but no mandatory regulatory threshold for dementia design — guidance-level only. Compare to NO Husbanken (funding-linked mandatory), IT DPCM/Ministry RSA (mandatory 1-in-3 dementia modules), DK Mærkningsordning (formal labelling scheme). Sources: dementia.stir.ac.uk (DSDC), stir.ac.uk/EADDAT-2022, kirklees.gov.uk/dementia-design-guide, digital.nhs.uk/dementia-friendly-environments-assessors, housinglin.org.uk/Dementia-Design, signageforcare.com/international-standards (comparative review), architectsdatafile.co.uk/Andrews-quote, rdscarebuild.com/UK-Care-Home-Design-2025. CONFIDENCE: high — primary authoritative sources (DSDC, NHS England, Kirklees Council) and quantified research findings.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:18:55.171889+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','ES','SEARCHED',8,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: **Guía de Práctica Clínica sobre la Atención Integral a las Personas con Enfermedad de Alzheimer y otras Demencias** — National Health System clinical practice guide, hosted by GuíaSalud (Plan de Calidad para el SNS del Ministerio de Sanidad, 2010), endorsed by multi-organization consortium (Alzheimer Catalunya, Fundació Pasqual Maragall, CEAFA, SEGG, SEMFyC, SEN, etc.). CRE Alzheimer (Centro de Referencia Estatal de Atención a Personas con Enfermedad de Alzheimer y otras Demencias) — IMSERSO (Ministerio de Servicios Sociales). Fundación Pilares "Buenas Prácticas" series. CEAFA (Confederación Española de Asociaciones de Familiares de Personas con Alzheimer). REGULATORY STATUS: Clinical practice guides (GPC) from SNS are official clinical guidance, not mandatory building code requirements. CTE DB SUA covers physical accessibility but does not specifically address dementia spatial cognition. Estado autonómico means design standards vary by autonomous community — Catalonia, Madrid, Basque Country have specific regional guidelines. KEY PRINCIPLES: (1) Cromoterapia (color therapy) used for identification and orientation. (2) Identification through characteristic local symbols (e.g., trees representing each module/zone). (3) Combined visual + written signage (pictograms + words). (4) Adapted calendars and clocks (large numbers, day/season indicators). (5) Interior patios providing natural light and ambulation zones. (6) Wide, well-lit, low-noise spaces. (7) Avoid strong/loud colors that cause stress; warm colors stimulate, cool colors calm. (8) Avoid sensory overstimulation. (9) Sociosanitary model emphasis. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: Spain has comprehensive clinical guidance but no dementia-specific building code provisions comparable to NO Husbanken funding requirements or DK Mærkningsordning. Regional autonomy creates variability. Sources: portal.guiasalud.es/gpc/alzheimer, blogcrea.imserso.es, fundacionpilares.org/buenas-practicas, paliativossinfronteras.org/OMC-guialazheimer. CONFIDENCE: high for guidance framework; medium for absence of mandatory standard.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:16:53.784184+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','ZH','SEARCHED',11,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11 (UPGRADE from 110-char pre-remediation stub). KEY INSTRUMENTS (LAYERED REGULATORY FRAMEWORK — MOST FORMAL IN COMPARISON SET): (1) **GB/T 46401-2025《养老机构认知障碍老年人照护指南》** — NATIONAL Recommended Standard, Care Guide for Elderly with Cognitive Impairment in Senior Care Institutions. (2) **DB 13/T 5544-2022《养老机构认知障碍友好环境设置导则》** — Hebei PROVINCIAL Local Standard, Dementia-Friendly Environment Design Guidelines. (3) **MZ/T 131-2019** — Ministry of Civil Affairs (民政部) standard for public information symbols, safety markers, text markers in senior care. (4) **JGJ 450** — Construction Industry Standard, lighting for elderly building Chapter 7 covers cognitive-impairment elderly lighting. (5) **团体标准《养老设施认知症照料单元设计导则》** — Group Standard, Dementia Care Unit Design Guideline. (6) **《养老机构等级划分与评定》国家标准** — National Standard for Grading and Evaluation of Senior Care Institutions. Academic: 周燕珉 (Zhou Yanmin, Tsinghua University) — leading dementia design researcher. REGULATORY STATUS: Multi-level mandatory + recommended framework. GB/T = National Recommended Standard (compliance affects facility grading). DB = Provincial Local Standard (mandatory in jurisdiction). MZ/T + JGJ = Industry mandatory standards. This is the MOST formalized regulatory framework in the comparison set specifically addressing dementia spatial design at the architectural detail level. KEY MANDATORY PROVISIONS (from DB 13/T 5544 §5 + group standard): (1) §5.1.10 Equipment/facilities should use colors elderly are sensitive to (e.g., bathroom door panels). (2) §5.2.1 Public symbols/safety markers/text markers must follow MZ/T 131-2019 §5-6. (3) §5.2.2 Signs for cognitive-impairment elderly MUST include text + image elements; simplified clear font; symbols/vectors/photos acceptable. (4) §5.2.3 Directional signs REQUIRED at main entrances, elevator lobbies, elevator interiors, corridor corners — with arrow direction. (5) §5.4.1 Lighting must comply with JGJ 450 §7. (6) §5.4.2 Multi-source combination lighting adjustable by time/weather/needs. (7) Outdoor: looped (环路) walking paths, simple/clear routes, interesting landmarks, color contrast at path boundaries. (8) Outdoor activity areas: gardening, intergenerational, pets, laundry-drying zones. (9) Aromatic plants and landmarks providing visual/olfactory/auditory cues. (10) Public toilet nearby outdoor activity. (11) Natural light in main activity and living spaces for temporal perception. (12) Open-style food preparation space within unit. (13) Hidden/locked storage for dangerous items (cleaning agents, knives). (14) Heating equipment with hidden master switch. (15) Self-service tea bar option for mild-moderate cognitive impairment. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: ZH has the most LEGALLY PRESCRIPTIVE mandatory framework — national + provincial + industry + construction standards addressing dementia spatial design at specific architectural detail level (door panel colors, sign positioning, lighting standards by section). This goes beyond NO Husbanken funding-linked requirements and IT DPCM facility-level mandates by specifying spatial details at the article level. Sources: GB/T 46401-2025 full text (thnet.gov.cn/attachment/46401-2025), DB 13/T 5544-2022 (fuxi365.com Hebei standard), MZ/T 131-2019, JGJ 450 (建筑标准), nxzw.gov.cn/养老机构等级划分与评定-国家标准实施指南, ttbz.org.cn/养老设施认知症照料单元设计导则 group standard. CONFIDENCE: high — primary multi-level standards confirmed; ZH framework documented at GB national, DB provincial, MZ/T industry, JGJ construction levels.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:20:52.313794+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','IT','SEARCHED',9,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: **DPCM 22/12/1989** (Decreto del Presidente del Consiglio dei Ministri) — primary mandatory regulation establishing RSA standards. **Linee guida del Ministero della Sanità sulle Residenze Sanitarie Assistenziali** — Ministry of Health guidelines defining architectural requirements. **Piano Nazionale Demenze** — National Dementia Plan policy document. DM 236/1989 (accessibility), DPR 503/1996 (public accessibility). REGULATORY STATUS: DPCM 22/12/1989 is legally mandatory. The RSA Ministry guidelines have de facto regulatory force as construction requirements. This is one of the most formalized frameworks in the set. MANDATORY RSA STRUCTURE: Average 4 modules of 20-25 residents, max 6 modules or 120 residents per facility. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: **1 of every 3 RSA modules MUST be reserved for dementia** (10-15 places per dementia module). Living spaces 1-3 beds max per room. This is a unique structural mandate in the comparison set. KEY ARCHITECTURAL PRINCIPLES: (1) Single-floor structure preferred. (2) "Leggibilità" (legibility) as core principle — comprehensibility/recognizability of spaces; communicate sense of space; give orientation messages; overcome serial anonymity. (3) Formal volumetric and differentiation of spaces. (4) Integrated signage system: materials, colors, lights, plants (not just graphics). (5) Common service nucleus (mensa, bar, soggiorno) in centric position. (6) Outdoor garden as daily landscape. (7) Wide barrier-free corridors. (8) Personalization of private spaces. (9) Color and light strategically used: warm colors (yellow/orange/red) for activity stimulation; cool colors (blue/green/violet) for relaxation. (10) Avoid loud/contrasting colors that overwhelm. Sources: gazzettaufficiale.it/DPCM-22-12-1989-RSA, fondazionepromozionesociale.it/Ministero-Linee-guida, valoreinrsa.it/Piano-Nazionale-Demenze, biblus.acca.it/casa-di-riposo-anziani-progettazione, harmoniecare.it/arredamento-rsa. CONFIDENCE: high for mandatory RSA framework and 1-in-3 dementia module requirement; high for ministry guidelines on architectural principles.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:16:53.784184+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','KO','SEARCHED',7,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: **제4차 치매관리종합계획 (2021-2025)** (4th National Dementia Management Comprehensive Plan, Ministry of Health and Welfare/MOHW — 보건복지부). 치매안심마을 (Dementia-Safe Village) — community-level program. 치매안심센터 (Dementia-Safe Center) — local centers across all districts. **인지건강 디자인 매뉴얼** (Cognitive Health Design Manual, Seoul Metropolitan Government, 2021 apartment-type version, originally 2016). **고령자 인지건강 디자인 가이드라인** (Elderly Cognitive Health Design Guideline) — KCDF (Korea Craft & Design Foundation). 노인요양시설 평가 매뉴얼 (Senior Care Facility Evaluation Manual). 노인복지법 (Welfare of the Aged Act, 1981 — legal basis). REGULATORY STATUS: National Dementia Management Plan is national policy. Senior care facility evaluation manual is mandatory for licensing/operation. Seoul''s 인지건강 디자인 (Cognitive Health Design) program is municipal regulation/guidance — comprehensive design framework. KEY PRINCIPLES: (1) 인지건강 디자인 (Cognitive Health Design) — distinct Korean concept. (2) Color contrast at apartment entrances for recognition. (3) Warm/cool color use to invite activity vs. calm. (4) Sign color saturation must be high (low chroma perceived as black, causing confusion). (5) Background-text color contrast on signs critical. (6) Eye-catching colors, larger sizes, directional markers on wayfinding signs. (7) Apartment-type cognitive health design with steps for safe outdoor activity. (8) Targeted at 50-60+ pre-dementia population for prevention. (9) Bottom-up community approach — 치매안심마을 builds dementia-friendly neighborhoods through community members becoming ''기억친구'' (memory friends). CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: KO has a unique COMMUNITY-LEVEL focus (dementia-safe villages, dementia-safe centers, memory friends) rather than primarily institution-level focus (DE/IT/FR EHPAD/RSA model). Korea''s approach emphasizes aging-in-place + community network alongside facility design. Sources: welfare.seoul.kr/Vol-145-치매돌봄, kcdf.or.kr/고령자-인지건강-디자인-가이드라인, publicdesign.kr/인지건강-디자인-매뉴얼-기획특집, mohw.go.kr/제4차-치매관리종합계획. CONFIDENCE: high for national plan and Seoul design manual; medium for absence of dedicated national facility design code beyond evaluation manual.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:16:53.784184+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','SV','SEARCHED',8,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: Socialstyrelsen "Nationella riktlinjer för vård och omsorg vid demenssjukdom" (National Guidelines for Dementia Care, recommendations and indicators). Myndigheten för delaktighet (Agency for Participation) "Miljöanpassningar som bidrar till ökad delaktighet". Svenskt Demenscentrum (Swedish Dementia Centre) — checklist for better living environment. Boverkets byggregler (BBR) §3:1423 (legally binding luminance contrast ≥0.40 NCS — overlaps with luminance-contrast slug). Key academic source: Helle Wijk (docent, Göteborgs universitet; Svenskt Demenscentrum) — leading Swedish research on dementia spatial design. REGULATORY STATUS: Socialstyrelsen Nationella riktlinjer = mandatory recommendations for municipal social services. BBR = legally binding building code. Svenskt Demenscentrum + Myndigheten för delaktighet = guidance. KEY RECOMMENDATIONS: (1) Small-scale environments — Socialstyrelsen recommends small units (75% of Swedish dementia homes already ≤10 rooms, typical 8 rooms). (2) Clear contrasts (BBR ≥0.40 NCS) without glare. (3) Avoid floors with strong patterns (perceived as uneven or dirty). (4) Color differences can be perceived as level differences in dementia — avoid stark color contrasts on thresholds/floors (perceived as holes). (5) Color-coded doors/zones for orientation. (6) Home-feeling (hemkänsla) through flexibility for residents to bring own belongings. (7) Choice between social and private spaces. (8) Accessible indoor and outdoor environments. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: SE uniquely combines (a) legally binding BBR contrast requirement (≥0.40 NCS) cross-referenced with (b) Socialstyrelsen guidelines on care unit scale (≤10 rooms). Few jurisdictions formally connect physical building code with dementia care standards. Sources: roi.socialstyrelsen.se/demenssjukdom, demenscentrum.se/checklista, arkitekt.se/fargsattning-tillgangliggor (Sveriges Arkitekter), boverket.se/BBR-3-1423, svenskbyggtidning.se/Wijk-research. CONFIDENCE: high for regulatory framework and key principles.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:13:18.717341+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','NL','SEARCHED',8,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11 (UPGRADE from 110-char pre-remediation stub). KEY INSTRUMENTS: **De Hogeweyk (Weesp)** — world''s first and most famous purpose-built dementia village, originated 2009; 27 houses, 6-7 residents each, organized into 4 lifestyle-based household types (Stads/Urban, Goois-Zuid/Wealthy, Cultureel/Cultural, Huiselijk/Homely); operates as a real neighborhood with shops, café, theater, supermarket within secure perimeter. **Toolkit Dementievriendelijk Woongebouw (2024)** — comprehensive guidance toolkit by Alzheimer Nederland + Woonzorg Nederland + Actiz + TU Eindhoven + KAW Architects + Aedes. Alzheimer Nederland — primary patient advocacy organization with research-based guidance. Platform31 — research network with 10 tips for dementia-friendly living. RIVM (Rijksinstituut voor Volksgezondheid en Milieu) — assessed De Hogeweyk for evidence base. Zorg voor Beter (government portal). Wlz (Wet Langdurige Zorg, Long-term Care Act) — governs nursing home regulation. Bouwbesluit/Bbl (Building Decree) — general accessibility, not specifically dementia. Omgevingswet / Omgevingsvisie (Environment Act/Vision, 2024) — provides legal framework for dementia-friendly living environments. REGULATORY STATUS: No mandatory regulatory framework specifically for dementia spatial design. Wlz governs nursing home delivery standards (kleinschalig wonen / small-scale living principle widely accepted but not legally specified). Toolkit Dementievriendelijk Woongebouw is comprehensive guidance from major sector organizations but not legally binding. De Hogeweyk model has been studied internationally and influences but does not codify standards. KEY PRINCIPLES (De Hogeweyk model and Toolkit): (1) Kleinschalig wonen (small-scale living) — 6-7 residents per household. (2) LIFESTYLE-BASED grouping (UNIQUE TO NL) — residents grouped by life style preferences (urban, wealthy, cultural, homely), not by care level. Environment configured to match lifestyle. (3) Each household has own front door — domestic-scale entry. (4) Residents move freely within secure community perimeter. (5) Real-neighborhood facilities (shops, café, theater) encourage stimulation/activity. (6) High color contrast at doors and stairs. (7) Pleasant lighting, natural materials. (8) Material-based wayfinding (texture, color, smell) rather than directional signage. (9) 3-5x more light needed than younger people. (10) Separate bedrooms for partner option (due to night agitation). (11) 79% of Dutch dementia patients live at home — toolkit addresses both home/community and institutional design. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: NL pioneered the dementia village concept (Hogeweyk, 2009 — globally most-replicated dementia design innovation). LIFESTYLE-BASED grouping is unique — most jurisdictions cluster by care needs, not lifestyle preferences. NL approach makes the ENTIRE ENVIRONMENT recognizable to a specific lifestyle, rather than relying on directional signage. Sources: rivm.nl/De-Hogeweyk-zo-gewoon-mogelijk, aedes.nl/Toolkit-Dementievriendelijk-Woongebouw, alzheimer-nederland.nl/Voorbeelden-Dementievriendelijke-Woningen, platform31.nl/Tien-Tips, zorgvoorbeter.nl/Leefomgeving, zorgsaamwonen.nl/Dementievriendelijk-wonen. CONFIDENCE: high — Hogeweyk model and Toolkit primary sources confirmed; medium for absence of specific national regulation (Wlz/Bbl exist but don''t mandate dementia spatial specifics).','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:20:52.313794+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','PT','PARTIAL',4,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: AFID Senior / Fundação AFID Diferença — practical Portuguese institution with UNE (Unidade de Neuroestimulação) project including Snoezelen room. DL 161/2006 (covers physical accessibility, not specifically dementia spatial design). Estruturas Residenciais para Pessoas Idosas (ERPI) — Social Security framework for residential structures for elderly, regulated through Instituto da Segurança Social. Reference sources include Brazilian neuroarquitetura literature (ArchDaily, IPH — Instituto de Pesquisas Hospitalares). novocuidar.pt practical guidance. REGULATORY STATUS: No dedicated formal Portuguese regulatory framework for dementia spatial design found in this search. ERPI licensing requires general care quality standards but does not specify dementia-specific architectural mandates comparable to IT DPCM/Ministry RSA guidelines, NO Husbanken funding requirements, or DK Mærkningsordning. GAP: Portuguese national plan for dementia and its building/design components — not retrieved. Specific Portuguese guidance from Ministério da Saúde or Instituto da Segurança Social on dementia facility design — not retrieved. Lar de idosos design standards beyond general ERPI requirements — not retrieved. KEY PRINCIPLES (from non-regulatory sources): (1) Color contrast for orientation; (2) Easy-to-read clocks and calendars; (3) Acoustic damping; (4) Warm light (2800K) at night; (5) Snoezelen rooms; (6) Connection to nature; (7) Curving paths and clear sightlines. Sources: afidsenior.pt/UNE-projeto, novocuidar.pt/casa-mais-favoravel, iph.org.br/arquitetura-hospitalar-sensivel-demencia, archdaily.com.br/neuroarquitetura-demencia, espacodearquitetura.com/neuroarquitetura-demencia. CONFIDENCE: high for absence of dedicated mandatory framework; low for Portuguese national policy/guidance documents (not retrieved if they exist).','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:16:53.784184+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','NO','SEARCHED',10,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11. KEY INSTRUMENTS: **Helsedirektoratet Nasjonal faglig retningslinje for demens** (National Professional Guideline for Dementia) — mandatory national guidance. Demensplan 2025 (Dementia Plan 2025, builds on Demensplan 2015 + 2020 — national policy plan). Helsedirektoratet "Botilbud ved demens" (Living Arrangements for Dementia) — sub-guideline (siste faglige endring 2022). Husbanken (Norwegian State Housing Bank) — funding conditions REQUIRE that sykehjem (nursing homes) and omsorgsboliger (care homes) be adapted for dementia to receive construction tilskudd (subsidy). Veileder for lokalisering og utforming av omsorgsbygg (Husbanken). REGULATORY STATUS: This is the MOST FORMAL framework in the comparison set — Helsedirektoratet retningslinjer are forankret i lov/forskrift (anchored in law/regulation); Husbanken funding requirement makes dementia adaptation effectively mandatory for any new build receiving state subsidy. KEY PRINCIPLES ("Smått er godt" = "Small is good"): (1) Small units 4-12 residents (typical 8) — Demensplan 2025 emphasis. (2) >80% of all nursing home residents actually have dementia → adapt all units. (3) Bright corridors with daylight access. (4) Wide corridors (two wheelchairs/walkers can pass). (5) Well-marked rooms with personal identifiers (biographic photos/objects). (6) Windows along corridors for daylight, supporting orientation. (7) Doors along sides of corridor (not end position). (8) Less visible exit signs; exit doors look like other doors. (9) Non-transparent doors (no window). (10) Doors face safe environments like garden. (11) Direct outdoor access. (12) Use of color, signs, marking, support handles. (13) Floor materials that prevent falls. (14) Window locks limiting opening direction. (15) Avoid windows down to floor (residents may fear falling out). CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: NO uniquely ties dementia spatial design to construction FUNDING — Husbanken won''t fund non-adapted facilities. This is the most directly enforceable framework among the 14 jurisdictions. NO 4-12 residents matches DE 5-15 and SE typical 8. Sources: helsedirektoratet.no/Nasjonal-faglig-retningslinje-for-demens, helsedirektoratet.no/Botilbud-ved-demens, husbanken.no/Veileder-utforming-omsorgsbygg, Helsedirektoratet Demensplan 2025. CONFIDENCE: high — primary mandatory framework with direct regulatory force.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:15:02.510991+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('wayfinding-dementia-spatial-design','JA','SEARCHED',9,'TIER2 NATIVE SEARCH 2026-05-11 (UPGRADE from 110-char pre-remediation stub). KEY INSTRUMENTS: **厚生労働省令第34号 (MHLW Ordinance No. 34, "指定地域密着型サービスの事業の人員、設備及び運営に関する基準")** — mandatory standards for 認知症対応型共同生活介護 (Dementia-Adapted Communal Living Care / Group Homes). **認知症対応型共同生活介護 (Group Home)** — formally regulated service type under 介護保険 (Long-term Care Insurance), classified as 地域密着型サービス (Community-Based Services). **政府認知症施策推進基本計画** (Government Basic Plan for Dementia Policy Promotion, 2024 — under "新しい認知症観" / New View of Dementia approach). **認知症ケアパス** (Dementia Care Path, MHLW) — area-specific care pathway concept. **意思決定支援ガイドライン** (Decision-Making Support Guidelines for People with Dementia, MHLW 2018). REGULATORY STATUS: Highly formalized. Ministerial Ordinance No. 34 establishes MANDATORY facility standards. Group Home certification requires meeting all 指定基準 (designation standards): 人員基準, 設備基準, 運営基準. Local government (市町村) administers under national framework. MANDATORY FACILITY STANDARDS (per MHLW Ordinance 34): (1) Unit (ユニット) size: 5-9 residents per unit. (2) Maximum 2 units per facility = 18 residents max per facility — the SMALLEST mandatory scale in the comparison set. (3) Individual private rooms required (個室); min 7.43 m² per room. (4) Required common spaces per unit: kitchen, dining, toilets, washing area, bath, fire suppression (sprinklers). (5) Equipment must be separated per unit — no sharing between units. (6) Staffing: 1:3 daytime, ≥1 night staff. (7) Location must allow family/community interaction (地域密着 community-based principle). KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES: (1) 家庭的環境 (homelike environment), explicitly not institutional (not 病院 or 特別養護老人ホーム-like). (2) "なじみの関係" (familiar relationship) formation reduces behavioral problems. (3) Stable, low-change environment. (4) Residents participate in cooking, cleaning, laundry as 生活リハビリ (life rehabilitation). (5) Community/family integration through seasonal events. (6) Forms vary: 民家型 (house-type), アパート型 (apartment-type), ミニ施設型 (mini-facility-type). (7) No barriers, ensuring no blind spots in space layout. (8) New 2024 plan: "新しい認知症観" emphasizing hope-based living with dementia. CRITICAL DIVERGENCE: JA mandates ≤9 residents per unit and ≤18 per facility — the STRICTEST mandatory small-scale requirement. Compare: IT max 120/RSA, DE 5-15 typical (guidance), NO 4-12 (guidance), SE 8 typical (guidance), DK no specific number. JA''s mandatory legal threshold makes its scale requirement uniquely enforceable. Sources: mhlw.go.jp/content/12300000/000647295.pdf (MHLW Group Home overview), mhlw.go.jp/content/12300000/001113811.pdf (令和3年度介護報酬改定), kaigokensaku.mhlw.go.jp (official介護サービス情報公表システム), nippku.com/group_home/施設基準, care21.co.jp/dementia-group-home-guide, mhlw.go.jp/decision-support-guideline-2018, tyojyu.or.jp/group. CONFIDENCE: high — primary mandatory regulation (Ordinance 34) and MHLW documents directly cited.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11T04:20:52.313794+00:00','session_2026-05-11e-wayfinding-dementia');
