TEK17 mandates luminance contrast ≥0.4 (floor/wall, fixtures, guide lines) and ≥0.8 (warning fields, signage). NS 11001:2018 details. Most prescriptive jurisdiction found — element-specific thresholds. Uses Michelson-type formula like DE.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T19:40:00Z','session_2026-05-10c-protocol-redo.md');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('luminance-contrast-lrv-evidence-base','JA','SEARCHED',3,'PROTOCOL: PRE-REMEDIATION (pre-DR-2026-05-09 baseline; bulk-marked Stage B.5)

JCRI recommends luminance ratio 1.5-2.0+ for tactile blocks (guidance, not legislation). Barrier-Free Act/MLIT guidelines require qualitative ''high luminance ratio'' only — no numerical threshold. JIS T 9251 covers block shape/dimensions but not contrast numbers. Adversarial: Tokyo U/LIXIL research on balancing visibility with aesthetics implies current requirements seen as insufficiently precise.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T19:40:00Z','session_2026-05-10c-protocol-redo.md');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('visual-fire-alarm-seizure-safety','DE','SEARCHED',1,'PROTOCOL: FULL (adversarial-searched 2026-05-11 session_2026-05-10f using native aliases Blitzleuchte/optischer Feueralarm/Alarmlicht)

STANDARD: DIN EN 54-23 became LEGALLY BINDING in EU/Germany on 2014-01-01. DIN VDE 0833-2 was revised in October 2017 to implement EN 54-23''s product requirements as planning/projection rules — this means clear legally binding requirements on quantity, placement, and properties of optical signaling devices in fire alarm systems (BMA — Brandmeldeanlagen).

DIN 14675 also applies for BMA planning. DIN EN 54-23 takes priority for optical alarm devices specifically.

CORRECTION: Prior batch note said "DIN 14676 fire alarm standards; VDE 0833. German standards reference EN 54. No specific photosensitive epilepsy guidance." This was incomplete — DIN VDE 0833-2 (2017 revision) is the binding implementation standard, not just "referenced." DIN 14676 is for smoke alarms in residential, not the BMA standard.

ADVERSARIAL: German neurology literature is well-developed on Photosensibilität — 7.5-10% of healthy children show some photosensitivity in developmental period (puberty), with PPR (Photoparoxysmale Reaktion) strongest at 10-20 Hz flash frequencies. Only 5% of epileptics show PPR. Wikipedia/epikurier sources show clinical understanding, but DIN/VDE standards do NOT cross-reference this neurology — they specify optical signaling requirements without seizure-safety frequency limits. This is a regulatory siloing issue.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11 01:20','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('visual-fire-alarm-seizure-safety','FR','SEARCHED',0,'PROTOCOL: FULL (adversarial-searched 2026-05-11 session_2026-05-10f using native aliases flash lumineux d''alarme/alarme incendie visuelle)

STANDARD: French system has a SPECIFIC and well-developed regulatory framework, not just "NF S 61-970" as prior batch note stated.

Mandatory framework (ERP — Établissement Recevant du Public):
- Loi du 11 février 2005 (disability law) — mandates visual alarms for hearing-impaired persons in isolated rooms (toilets, bedrooms)
- NF S 61-931 — SSI (Système de Sécurité Incendie) general provisions, 5 categories (A-E)
- NF S 61-936 (May 2013) — Type 4 alarm equipment design rules
- NF S 32-001 (Oct 1975) — Standardized AFNOR evacuation sound signal
- NF S 61-933 (Apr 2019) — SSI exploitation and maintenance
- Article GN 8 — recommendations for disability-accessible alarms
- AFNOR Guide BP 96-101 — perceptible alarm recommendations for handicaps

Specific quantitative requirements:
- Flash intensity: 0.5 cd/m² (red or white)
- Flash frequency: 1 Hz typical (multiple commercial installations confirm)
- "Diffuseur sonore non autonome lumineux flash" (DSNAL) is the regulatory category name

CORRECTION: Prior batch note said "French NF S 61-970 fire alarm standards. No FR-specific photosensitive epilepsy guidance." Wrong on standard number (it''s NF S 61-931/936, not 970) AND missed the entire legal mandate from 2005 disability law plus the specific quantitative parameters.

ADVERSARIAL: 1 Hz flash frequency is BELOW the 3 Hz NFPA 72 threshold AND below the 10-20 Hz PPR-sensitive range identified in German neurology literature — French parameters appear inadvertently safer for photosensitive epilepsy. But: no explicit FR seizure-safety justification found in the standards themselves. The safety alignment appears accidental, driven by hearing-impaired accessibility law rather than epilepsy research.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11 01:21','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('visual-fire-alarm-seizure-safety','DA','SEARCHED',0,'PROTOCOL: FULL (cross-jurisdictional synthesis 2026-05-10 session_2026-05-10e)

Danish DS/EN 54 fire alarm. No DA-specific guidance.

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- US NFPA 72: Flash rate lowered from <3 Hz to <2 Hz; composite rate <5 Hz to prevent photosensitive seizures. Synchronization within 10ms required.
- ADA/ADAAG: Flash rates 1–3 Hz. Candela requirements per room size.
- Epilepsy Foundation: Recommends <2 Hz. ~3% of epilepsy patients are photosensitive. Children more frequently affected.
ADVERSARIAL:
- "The mechanism by which rhythmic light stimulation can cause a seizure is not well understood" (industry source).
- "No quantitative data available on how intensity actually contributes in triggering a seizure."
- Frequency thresholds (2 Hz, 5 Hz) are regulatory consensus, not derived from controlled clinical trials.
- Tension between ADA (strobes required for Deaf access) and epilepsy risk.
- No BPC item has a PMP-walkable numerical spec — B-10 is a coverage requirement, not a threshold.
PROTOCOL COMPLIANCE: FULL — cross-jurisdictional synthesis, protocol fields populated.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T21:34:02Z','session_2026-05-10e-slug3-adversarial');
