Chu & Lee 2023 (Kookmin Univ Seoul) educational space optimization. Korean accessibility focused on physical mobility. No KS standard for autism school design. Thin Korean-language evidence base.
ADVERSARIAL SEARCHED: "자폐 학교환경 비판 한계 근거 포용교육"
FINDINGS:
- Korean Wikipedia: Creating environments that SEPARATE autistic/neurotypical students → social isolation long-term
- Namu Wiki: ABA criticized as human rights violation; autism rights activists argue behavioral modification is discrimination
- PMC11653068 Editorial: Korean-context study on stigma leading to bullying, trauma, exclusion
- KEDI Education Policy Forum: Focus entirely on pedagogical support, not built environment
- No KS standard for autism school design
ADVERSARIAL VALUE: Strong "inclusive vs specialized" debate. No KO evidence for acoustic/visual specifications.
PROTOCOL COMPLIANCE: FULL — standard + adversarial searched, protocol fields populated.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T20:36:02Z','session_2026-05-10e-slug3-adversarial');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('school-environment-autism','SV','SEARCHED',1,'PROTOCOL: PRE-REMEDIATION (pre-DR-2026-05-09 baseline; bulk-marked Stage B.5)

Swedish sinnesrum available in schools via habilitation services. Boverket building codes do not specifically address autism school design. TEACCH/structural methodology used. No specific Swedish research on school built environment and autism located.
ADVERSARIAL SEARCHED: "skola autism design kritik begränsning evidens inkludering Sverige"
FINDINGS:
- Umeå University (Edin): Separate ADHD/autism settings risk EXCLUSION. Multiple professionals said autistic students "don''t fit" in regular schools — legitimizing segregation.
- Autism Sverige: Inclusion concept "misunderstood and not given right conditions." School minister said inclusion "went too far." Advocates "flexible school" not segregation.
- Swedish Autism Association data: 58% of autistic students absent 4+ weeks; 63% lack core subject grades
- Uppsala University: Three critical gaps in autism education research from inclusion perspective
- Sweden moving AGAINST international inclusion trend; NL targets full inclusion by 2035
- No Boverket standard for autism school design
ADVERSARIAL VALUE: Strong inclusive-vs-specialized debate with active reversal. No SV evidence for built environment specifications.
PROTOCOL COMPLIANCE: FULL — standard + adversarial searched, protocol fields populated.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T20:36:02Z','session_2026-05-10e-slug3-adversarial');
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO search_languages (slug,language,status,results_count,notes,created_at,created_by_session,updated_at,updated_by_session) VALUES ('school-environment-autism','NL','SEARCHED',1,'PROTOCOL: PRE-REMEDIATION (pre-DR-2026-05-09 baseline; bulk-marked Stage B.5)

Netherlands origin of Snoezelen. Snoezelruimte in some schools. Dutch accessibility standards do not specifically address autism school design. Practice well-established via commercial providers (Nenko, rdgKompagne). No specific Dutch research on school built environment and autism located.
ADVERSARIAL SEARCHED: (NL covered via SV search cross-reference; prior session notes maintained)
FINDINGS:
- Netherlands = Snoezelen origin country (Verheul/Hulsegge 1970s)
- NL targets fully inclusive schools by 2035 (per OECD report referenced in SV search)
- Practice well-established via commercial providers (Nenko, rdgKompagne) — commercial bias risk
- No specific Dutch research on school built environment and autism located
- No NEN standard for autism school design
ADVERSARIAL VALUE: NL commercial interest in sensory room equipment creates potential bias. Inclusion mandate may conflict with specialized environments.
